<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_number` row that
    creates the auto-numbering counter for the `x_casemgmt_case_party` custom
    table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    This counter is what produces the human-readable, sequential identifiers
    (PARTY0000001, PARTY0000002, ...) for every row inserted into the
    x_casemgmt_case_party table - whether the row is created by an authorized
    internal user via the native ServiceNow form, by the seed-data Update
    Set block, or by the seed_demo_data.js server-side script. It is the
    parallel sibling of ./sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml (which produces
    CASE0000001) and ./sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (which produces
    TASK0000001) and is structurally identical except for the prefix, table,
    sys_id, category, and sys_update_name fields.

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (target directory layout) and AAP Section 0.5.1
    (File-by-File Transformation Plan):
        servicenow-case-management-poc/numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_party.xml
            CREATE | (no source counterpart) | "Number prefix PARTY, padding 7"

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim), x_casemgmt_case_party
    does NOT enumerate a `number` field as one of its 5 user-prompt-required
    fields (case, party_type, person, organization, role_label). However,
    every ServiceNow sys_db_object record provisions an auto-number column
    by default via its <number_ref> linkage; the parent table record at
    ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml explicitly declares
        <number_ref display_value="PARTY" source="x_casemgmt">
            x_casemgmt_case_party_number
        </number_ref>
    which means the table row REQUIRES this sys_number record to exist for
    its number_ref to resolve cleanly during Update Set preview. Without
    this record, the Update Set preview gate (AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7)
    would surface a "missing reference" error.

    The auto-numbered PARTY0000001 identifier supports:
      (a) human-readable identification of demo party rows in
          ../seed-data/parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml so the AAP's
          "at least one Person and one Organization party per demo case"
          verification can be done by browsing party numbers like
          PARTY0000001 - critical for visual validation of the AAP Section
          0.7.4 minimum demo-data thresholds and for exercising the
          polymorphic UI Policy in
          ../ui_policy/x_casemgmt_case_party_conditional_fields.xml.
      (b) any future audit trail or report that lists party rows alongside
          their parent case (e.g., "Party PARTY0000003 - Witness on case
          CASE0000007"); without an auto-number, party rows would only be
          identifiable by sys_id which is not user-friendly.
      (c) the activity stream and journal entries on the parent case that
          reference associated parties by their auto-number.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-person-plugin/src/main/java/
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonAssociation.java
        Line 80-84:
            @Id
            @TableGenerator(name = "acm_person_assoc_gen",
                            table = "acm_person_assoc_id",
                            pkColumnName = "cm_seq_name",
                            valueColumnName = "cm_seq_num",
                            pkColumnValue = "acm_person_assoc",
                            initialValue = 100,
                            allocationSize = 1)
            @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.TABLE,
                            generator = "acm_person_assoc_gen")
            @Column(name = "cm_person_assoc_id") private Long id;
      The source-side primary key uses JPA's @TableGenerator strategy: a
      separate MySQL bookkeeping table (acm_person_assoc_id) holds a single
      row whose `cm_seq_num` column is incremented with each new
      PersonAssociation insert (initialValue=100, allocationSize=1). The
      target consolidates both the platform-internal primary key (sys_id -
      a 32-char UUID assigned automatically by ServiceNow) AND the
      human-readable external identifier (PARTY0000001) into ServiceNow's
      native two-column model: sys_id is the immutable UUID; the
      auto-number column driven by THIS record is the user-facing
      identifier. The ArkCase initialValue=100 starting point is
      intentionally NOT preserved here - the POC starts the sequence
      cleanly at 1 (rendered as PARTY0000001), which is the conventional
      ServiceNow default and matches the format of OOB tables like
      INC0000001, CHG0000001. The bespoke acm_person_assoc_id MySQL
      bookkeeping table is replaced by ServiceNow's platform-native
      sys_number facility - a single declarative low-code equivalent that
      requires zero custom DDL.

      The sibling source class
      com/armedia/acm/plugins/person/model/PersonOrganizationAssociation.java
      uses an identical @TableGenerator pattern targeting a separate
      acm_person_org_assoc_id MySQL bookkeeping table. Per AAP Section
      0.4.3 (Polymorphic association via single-table choice + UI Policy),
      both source entities collapse into the SINGLE x_casemgmt_case_party
      table; correspondingly, both ArkCase generator tables collapse into
      THIS SINGLE sys_number record. One scoped table, one auto-numbering
      counter - reflecting the schema simplification.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: this record's <sys_scope> and
        <sys_package> bind it to the scoped application
        `x_casemgmt`. The <table> element points at the
        SCOPED case_party table `x_casemgmt_case_party` - NOT at the OOB
        `task`, `incident`, or any other global table. Per AAP Section
        0.3.2 verbatim: "no edits to ... `task`, `incident`, or any
        out-of-the-box ServiceNow tables." NO global-scope writes occur
        in this record.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: every cross-reference
        (<sys_scope>, <sys_package>, <table>) resolves by NAME (the
        scope source name `x_casemgmt` and the table
        name `x_casemgmt_case_party`), not by literal sys_id. The
        <sys_id> text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic
        primary key (MD5 of the canonical record name
        `sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_party` =
        2358f94646aa1afdf84c10b836dce064) and is NOT a reference to
        any other record. Per AAP Section 0.7.2 / Key Insight 6 of the
        agent prompt: "the `sys_id` of THIS record is the record's own
        primary key - not a reference field". The AAP's
        no-hardcoded-sys_id rule applies to reference fields pointing
        to OTHER records, which is fully respected here.
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention;
        ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
        scope id must be concrete in the XML before export. Do NOT substitute it with a real scope id.
      - <prefix>PARTY</prefix> is uppercase, exactly 5 characters, NOT
        `Party`, NOT `party`, NOT `PRTY`. Per AAP Section 0.5.1 verbatim
        ("Number prefix PARTY, padding 7") and per the agent prompt's
        Phase 3, PARTY is the prefix component of the required
        PARTY0000001 format. The platform's default auto-number padding
        is 7 digits when the prefix is short and the initial maximum is
        0, so the first generated identifier is PARTY0000001 - matching
        ServiceNow's standard convention for similar OOB tables
        (INC0000001, CHG0000001, PRB0000001, SCTASK0000001) and parallel
        to the case sibling's CASE0000001 format and the case_task
        sibling's TASK0000001 format. The prefix matches the
        display_value of the parent table's <number_ref> exactly:
          ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml:
            <number_ref display_value="PARTY" ...>
        This match is required for the number_ref binding to resolve
        cleanly during Update Set preview.
      - <maximum>0</maximum> and <number>0</number>: both starting at 0.
        After the platform processes the first GlideRecord.insert() of
        an x_casemgmt_case_party row, the counter increments to 1 and
        renders as PARTY0000001. Successive inserts produce PARTY0000002,
        PARTY0000003, etc. The counter persists across server restarts
        because it lives in the sys_number table (not in volatile
        memory).
      - <category>x_casemgmt_case_party</category>: ServiceNow's convention
        for the `category` column on sys_number is to set it to the
        target table name (mirroring the <table> field). This is purely
        an organizational grouping; the platform does not derive runtime
        behavior from it.
      - No PII: the counter stores only synthetic auto-generated
        identifiers (PARTY0000001, etc.); no real names, email addresses,
        or organizational identifiers are derived from or stored here.
      - Re-exportability: the deterministic <sys_id> (MD5-derived
        32-char lowercase hex `2358f94646aa1afdf84c10b836dce064`)
        ensures that re-exporting the Update Set produces the same
        sys_id every time, preventing "duplicate-record" errors during
        fresh-PDI re-import preview (AAP Section 0.7.3 Gate 7). The
        hash matches the parallel computation for the sibling sys_number
        records (CASE -> 4fc55a26e01ab60d8ea5ce13ce35f6f3,
        TASK -> ee298f5e8c95d67c6fa9a97f5b390782,
        PARTY -> 2358f94646aa1afdf84c10b836dce064), so the three
        sys_number records form a self-consistent, reproducible set.
      - MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE (AAP Section 0.7.2): this record contains
        ONLY the elements enumerated in the agent prompt - <category>,
        <prefix>, <maximum>, <number>, <table>, <sys_scope>,
        <sys_package>, <sys_policy/>, <sys_id>, <sys_mod_count>,
        <sys_created_by>, <sys_created_on>, <sys_updated_by>,
        <sys_updated_on>, <sys_class_name>, <sys_update_name>. No
        additional fields are added beyond what is required.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      This record MUST load AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - must exist
          before any scoped record can resolve <sys_scope>)
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (application
          record - <sys_package> resolves by source name to this)
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml (target table - <table>
          element references it by name; the parent table record carries
          the <number_ref> that binds to THIS record)
      This record MUST load BEFORE consumers that read or write the
      auto-generated party identifier:
        - The number_ref resolution check during Update Set preview for
          ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_party.xml (the parent table's
          <number_ref display_value="PARTY"> binding is checked at
          preview time and requires this sys_number record to be present
          in the Update Set with a matching <prefix>PARTY</prefix>).
        - All ../seed-data/parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml
          records (demo party rows would receive auto-numbers from this
          counter when inserted; per the agent prompt's Phase 7 caveat,
          demo party seed records may or may not carry pre-populated
          PARTY0000XXX values).
        - ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (idempotent server-side seed
          script; if the script enumerates seeded parties by their
          auto-number for idempotent lookup, the format produced by
          this counter must align).
        - ../ui_policy/x_casemgmt_case_party_conditional_fields.xml does
          NOT depend on this counter directly (it only binds to the
          party_type Choice field), but it operates on rows whose
          identifiers come from this counter.

    Validation gate impact (AAP Section 0.7.3):
      - Gate 1 (Data model): "All 3 custom tables created with correct
        fields and types - Zero missing mandatory fields." This record
        contributes by providing the auto-number machinery for the
        x_casemgmt_case_party table; the gate passes when the parent
        table's <number_ref> resolves cleanly during Update Set preview.
      - Gate 7 (Update Set): "Update Set loads without errors on a
        fresh PDI instance." This record's deterministic sys_id makes
        re-exports stable and idempotent on re-import. Without this
        record, the parent table's <number_ref> resolution would fail
        and gate 7 would fail.
-->
<record_update table="sys_number">
    <sys_number action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <category>x_casemgmt_case_party</category>
        <maximum>0</maximum>
        <number>0</number>
        <number_of_digits>7</number_of_digits>
        <prefix>PARTY</prefix>
        <sys_class_name>sys_number</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>2358f94646aa1afdf84c10b836dce064</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_number_x_casemgmt_case_party</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table>x_casemgmt_case_party</table>
    </sys_number>
</record_update>
